'''Giovanni Battista Boazio''' or '''Battista Boazio''' ([[fl.]] 1588 – 1606) was an Italian draftsman and cartographer. He mapped Sir [[Francis Drake]]'s voyage to the West Indies and America. [[File:Boazio-Sir Francis Drake in Cartagena.jpg|thumb|Sir Francis Drake in Cartagena.]]
He spent a long period working in England, and made a map of Ireland that was then used in the ''[[Theatrum Orbis Terrarum]]''. He was sponsored by [[Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex]] to draw a map illustrating the [[Capture of Cadiz]], which was engraved by [[Thomas Cockson]].<ref>Paul E. J. Hammer, ''The Polarisation of Elizabethan Politics: the political career of Robert Devereux, 2nd Earl of Essex, 1585-1597'' (1999), p. 253 note 304; [https://books.google.com/books?id=VbKM-1eXuBkC&pg=PA253 Google Books].</ref> Other cartographic drawings includes [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena de las Indias]], [[Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic|Santo Domingo]] in the island of Hispaniola, [[Saint Augustine, Florida]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/kislak/kislak-exhibit.html|title=The Cultures and History of the Americas: The Jay I. Kislak Collection at the Library of Congress|author=Jay I. Kislak|publisher=Library of Congress}}</ref> and the Cape Verdean island of [[Santiago, Cape Verde|Santiago]], the Santiago engraving was one of the first to depict of that of any island in Cape Verde. {{Commons category|Baptista Boazio}}
==References== *Carl Moreland and David Bannister (1986), ''Antique Maps'', p.&nbsp;71.
