[[File:Start launch big.jpg|thumb|Start-1 launch vehicle lifting off from the Svobodny Cosmodrome]] '''Svobodny''' ({{lang-ru|Свобо́дный}}) was a [[Russia]]n [[rocket]] launch site located approximately 15km north of [[Svobodny, Amur Oblast]]. The [[cosmodrome]] was originally constructed as a launch site for [[intercontinental ballistic missile]]s called ''Svobodny-18''. It was initially selected as a replacement for [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] in the [[Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic]], which became independent as [[Kazakhstan]] after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]]. However the development of Svobodny was subsequently ended in 2007 in favour of a totally new space port, the [[Vostochny Cosmodrome]].
The breakup of the [[Soviet Union]] left the primary cosmodrome, to be used by successor state [[Russia]], at Baikonur in a foreign country, Kazakhstan. An arrangement to rent the facilities for $115 million annually was arranged. Launches were moved to other facilities, like [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome]], but this location is too far north to be useful for many launches. Studies for a far-east location closer to the latitude of Baikonur started,{{when|date=November 2014}} and initially settled on the existing missile base at Svobodny. This was located near the railway station of [[Ledyanaya railway station|Ledyanaya]], and had been used for several decades by the 27th rocket division of Strategic Rocket Forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asimov.esrin.esa.it/export/SPECIALS/ESA_Permanent_Mission_in_Russia/SEMMBS0XDYD_0.html|title=Svobodny|publisher=ESA permanent mission to Russia|date=22 September 2004|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070609125952/http://asimov.esrin.esa.it/export/SPECIALS/ESA_Permanent_Mission_in_Russia/SEMMBS0XDYD_0.html|archivedate=9 June 2007|df=}}</ref> In the summer of 1994 president Yeltsin visited the town of [[Blagoveshensk]] and the modification of the launch pads in the site began shortly after.<ref>{{cite book|title=The rebirth of the Russian space program: 50 years after Sputnik|page=228|last=Harvey|first=Brian|year=2007|publisher=Springer Praxis|isbn=978-0-387-71354-0 |doi=10.1007/978-0-387-71356-4_6}}</ref> On March 1, 1996 the Russian president issued a decree formally declaring the site as a cosmodrome.<ref>Russian space chronology – from Yuri Gagarin to the international space station</ref>
Launches from Svobodny began in 1997, primarily the ''[[Start-1]]'' type, converted ICBMs. The facilities can also host rockets of the [[Rokot]] ([[UR-100N|SS-19]] based) class. Only five launches have taken place at the underused Svobodny site, the best known being the [[Israel]]i [[EROS B]] satellite on 25 April 2006 aboard a Start class rocket.
In 2005, after the lease renewal of the Baikonur Cosmodrome, the [[Russian Space Agency]] decided it did not require a second space launch complex, and in February 2007 president [[Vladimir Putin]] ordered Svobodny closed.<ref name="defensebrief">{{cite journal|last=Ionin|first=Andrey|title=Russia's Space Program in 2006: Some Progress but No Clear Direction|journal=[[Moscow Defense Brief]]|publisher=[[Centre for Analysis of Strategies and Technologies]]|issue=2/2007|accessdate=2009-05-27}}</ref> In February 2007, a [[ukaz|presidential decree]] formalized the closure of the launch facility in Svobodny. According to the Russian press, in the previous three years, government investments in Svobodny reached 350 million rubles.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}
==See also== * [[Vostochny Cosmodrome]] * [[Plesetsk Cosmodrome]] * [[Baikonur Cosmodrome]] * [[Kapustin Yar]]
